Jan 28 2008 	Great Value for the $$	I had a non-smoking room with a king bed. The room seemed to be recently renovated and the furnishings were reminiscent of those boutique hotels that are cropping up in the big cities. I was very impressed with the bed linens, none of those ubiquitous polyester bedcovers (see picture). The bed was firm but not hard. The room was small (but not European small) with enough room for two people. The bathroom counter and sink was below standard U.S. heights. I'm 5 foot 4 inches and I felt like a giant in there. The towels were neither threadbare nor fluffy and they did the job they were designed do. My room overlooked the Fremont Street Experience and I could hear a constant hum/thrum in the room at nights. The television small with limited free stations. I would like to have a better selection of channels. An mini-refigerator and a cofee maker would also have been nice. The only area in the room that didn't seem updated was where the luggage, clothes hangers and iron/ironing board were stored (see picture). There was also a &quot;safebox&quot; that locked with a key. It was pretty flimsy by way of a safe, but at least you could lock up any valuables.I had breakfast and dinner at the Paradise Buffet which served mediocre to average fare. I feel I got a good value for the price paid -- better ambience compared to a similarly priced (overpriced) property like Best Western, Ramada Inn, Hampton Inn, Holiday Inn and others of that calibre.	
