Jan 6 2008 	Our favorite hotel/casino in Vegas!	Let me start out by stating that we prefer Downtown to any other area of Vegas. While not as glitzy or ritzy, it has a more authentic, old-school feeling than the Disnyfied Strip that is more geared to adults than to families. That being said, the accomodations are generally not as luxurious as those found on the Strip, but there are several clean and comfortable hotels to choose from. But, who goes to Vegas to hang out in their hotel room anyway?We have stayed/played at the Fremont many times and always have a great time! We usually receive comps to stay there for free, but even if we don't have comps, it is our first choice of places to stay/play downtown. When we were planning our wedding (7/7/07 - an incredibly busy time in Vegas), I called the Fremont because they were sold out and we had no offers for that weekend. We were willing to pay for a room to stay there (over all other downtown hotels which had availability). When I told them that we had become engaged in their casino during our previous stay and that we were returning to Vegas to get married and would rather pay full rate to stay at the Fremont instead of any other hotel (many which had availability), they not only made room for us, but they comped our stay! This is indicative of the level of customer service and the generally warmer, more intimate atmosphere at the Fremont that keeps us coming back for more.The hotel was recently renovated and the rooms, while not expansive, are tasteful, clean, and cozy. We are always quite comfortable there. The check-in is quick and easy, and we always find the staff to be very accomodating.We always have a great time in the casino and rarely venture out to play elsewhere. The cocktail service is generally reliable, and the cocktail waitresses are friendly (Remember to tip your server! These ladies work hard!). Sometimes we win...sometimes we don't; however, we generally feel like we get decent play for our money (as opposed to some casinos that seem to suck the money out of our wallets).We have eaten weekend brunch there many times (champagne brunch on Saturdays and Sundays). While the selection is not overwhealming (as in some of the strip buffets) they hit the right notes. There is a carving station, omlette bar, cold seafood selection, salad bar, the usual breakfast selections, and some other various hot/cold foods. The food always hits the spot, and the servers aren't stingy with the champagne. Plus the price can't be beat!We've also dined at the Second Street Grill (the upscale restaurant in the center of the casino). This is one of the better restaurants in the downtown area. The menu leans toward &quot;pacific rim&quot; but also offers steaks and other more &quot;traditional&quot; dishes. The food is delicious and high-quality, the presentation is beautiful, and the room is warm and intimate. We have stayed at almost all the other hotels downtown (including the Golden Nugget [the most upscale hotel, but we found it to be large and impersonal and a bit snooty and wannabe strip-like], the Plaza [mixed experiences - it's been a while, but it felt a bit gritty back in the day], Vegas Club [OK rooms but lacks personality], Golden Gate [really quaint and cozy in a bygone ere kind of way and great shrimp cocktails], Four Queens [again, nice rooms but slightly impersonal], Binions [not the same since it lost the &quot;Horseshoe&quot;, the Benny's Natural breakfast special and the million dollar display], the Fitz [OK but generic], and Lady Luck [before it closed]) but our first choice for playing and staying downtown is easily the Fremont!	
